deck: British publisher formed in 1982 by Dez Skinn.
description:
In 1982 Dez Skinn formed the Quality Communications company to publish the anthology comic, Warrior, as well a single issue revival of Halls of Horror, which Dez had previously produced for Top Sellers Ltd (where it had been House of Hammer and then House of Horror before becoming Halls of Horror, and where Warrior hero Father Shandor first transferred from Hammer movie to printed page). Quality later reprinted strips from 2000 AD for the U.S. market, taking over the license and some of the existing titles from Eagle Comics. In 1990 they published Comic International which ran for 16 year before the publication was sold to Cosmic Publications.

More recently they have published Jack Kirby Quarterly and Toy Max, a magazine for toy collectors.
name: Quality Communications

deck: American publisher of fantasy and role-playing games
description: Originally based in Stone Mountain, Georgia, White Wolf publishes role-playing games, collectible card games, and fiction novels. Their most famous role-playing games include Exalted, a fantasy game with obvious anime influence; Street Fighter, based upon the popular Capcom video game franchise of the same name, and the World of Darkness games (originally consisting of Vampire: The Masquerade, Werewolf: The Apocalypse, and Mage: The Ascension, with other offerings shortly after). Aside from fiction published in the goth-punk World of Darkness setting, White Wolf has published fiction featuring Michael Moorcook's Elric and Nancy A. Collins' Sonja Blue novels. Several comic artists have provided interior and cover art for the company's role-playing offerings, including Guy Davis, Tony Harris, Glenn Fabry, and Tim Bradstreet. Because of the adult themes in the World of Darkness games as well as controversy derived from "vampire cult" murders in Florida, the company has been beset by critics and parent watchdog groups. Regardless, the company continues to publish today.
name: White Wolf Publishing Co.

description:
Slab-O-Concrete was founded as a publisher and mail order distributor in the 1990s by Peter Pavement, Dave Hanna, Emma Copsey, and Chris Tappenden.
The company would publish work by creators including Ian Carney, Alan Moore, Woodrow Phoenix, Ed Hillyer, Jessica Abel, Peter Blake and Peter Bagge. In 1998, they published four titles in association with Amnesty International, featuring work by Enrique Rodríguez, Peter Arkle, Dan Jones and Donna Mathes.
In 1999, as one of their final publications, they published the book, The Worm: The Longest Comic Strip in The World. The book was scripted by Alan Moore and Neil Gaiman, among others, and featured art from creators including Dave Gibbons, Charlie Adlard, Donald Rooum, Glenn Fabry, Ed Pinsent, John Bolton, Dave King, Bambos Georgiou, Myra Hancock, Mark Buckingham, Elitta Fell, Kevin O'Neill and David Lloyd. The project was based upon a one day event, held at the London Trocadero centre in 1991, in which the strip was drawn live in front of passers-by.
Slab-O-Concrete ceased publishing in 2001.
name: Slab-O-Concrete

deck: French publishing company active from the 1960s to early 1980s.
description: Lucienne Fonvieille had worked at French publishing house Mon Journal (a.k.a. Aventures & Voyages) from 1958 to 1963. Deciding to form his own publishing company, he founded Jeunesse & Vacances (Youth & Holiday), which launched its first title, Cartouche et Robin des Bois in September 1964. As time passed, Jeanesse & Vacances began reprinting foreign strips translated into French, most notably the British strip Robot Archie, first in Atoll and then his own title, Archie. The company also adapted the adventures of German space hero Perry Rhodan into comics in the title Perry le Fantastique. However, mounting costs saw page numbers drop and prices rise on Jeanesse & Vacances’ titles, and in turn sales dropped. The company ceased publishing in 1981.
name: Jeunesse et Vacances

description: Scion were a British publisher who ventured into comics in the later 1940s and early 1950s, during the period when wartime paper restrictions were gradually easing but import restrictions meant foreign comics remained in short supply. They published a series of one-shots , such as the "Big" comics in 1948 and 1949 (Big Atlantis Comic, Big Castle Comic, Big Chuckle Comic, Big Flame Comic, etc.), and the "Hero" series in 1951 and 1952 (Adventure Hero, Daring Hero, Detective Hero, Sea Hero, Sky Hero, Space Hero, etc.), as well as a few ongoing titles, such as Electroman Comics.
name: Scion

deck: British newspaper publisher that also dabbled in comics.
description: Primarily known as a newspaper publisher, like several of its rivals (cf Beaverbrook) News of the World also tried its hand at publishing comics during the 1950s. It was the original publisher of TV Comic, and also released the short lived "space age weekly" Rocket, which was edited by popular World War II fighter pilot Douglas Bader. Meanwhile, like other papers, the News of the World paper itself also carried strips, most notably Spotlight on Sally by Arthur Ferrier.
name: News of the World
